      <codes for the decls and the statements in the block> POP n -- n is the number of local variables; pop them
      java.lang.Object Codegen.visitBoolTypeTree(AST t) 
      java.lang.Object Codegen.visitCallTree(AST t)
      Generate codes for the call tree:

      <Codes to evaluate the arguments for the function> ARGS n where n is the number of args CALL functionName
      java.lang.Object Codegen.visitDeclTree(AST t)
      Generate codes for the Decl tree:

      LIT 0 -- 0 is the initial value for the variable record the frame offset of this variable for future references
      java.lang.Object Codegen.visitFormalsTree(AST t) 
      java.lang.Object Codegen.visitFunctionDeclTree(AST t)
      Generate codes for the function declaration; we'll also record the frame offsets for the formal parameters

      java.lang.Object Codegen.visitReturnTree(AST t)

    • Uses of AST in parser

      Methods in parser that return AST 
      Modifier and Type Method and Description
      AST Parser.execute()
      Execute the parse command
      AST Parser.rBlock()
      block -> '{' d* s* '}' ==> block
      AST Parser.rDecl()
      d -> type name ==> decl -> type name funcHead block ==> functionDecl
      AST Parser.rExpr()
      e -> se -> se '==' se ==> = -> se '!=' se ==> != -> se '<' se ==> < -> se '<=' se ==> <=
      AST Parser.rFactor()
      f -> '(' e ')' -> name -> -> name '(' (e list ',')? ')' ==> call
      AST Parser.rFunHead()
      funHead -> '(' (decl list ',')? ')' ==> formals note a funhead is a list of zero or more decl's separated by commas, all in parens
      AST Parser.rName()
      name ->
      AST Parser.rProgram()
      Program -> 'program' block ==> program
      AST Parser.rSimpleExpr()
      se -> t -> se '+' t ==> + -> se '-' t ==> - -> se '|' t ==> or This rule indicates we should pick up as many t's as possible; the t's will be left associative
      AST Parser.rStatement()
      S -> 'if' e 'then' block 'else' block ==> if -> 'while' e block ==> while -> 'return' e ==> return -> block -> name '=' e ==> assign
      AST Parser.rTerm()
      t -> f -> t '*' f ==> * -> t '/' f ==> / -> t '&' f ==> and This rule indicates we should pick up as many f's as possible; the f's will be left associative
      AST Parser.rType()
      type -> 'int' type -> 'bool'
